## Why Cursor-Based Pagination is Superior Here

### The core problem with `OFFSET`

`OFFSET N` tells the database: *"scan through N rows and throw them away."* At `OFFSET 10000`, the DB reads and discards 10,000 rows on every request. Performance degrades **linearly** with page depth — page 500 is 500× slower than page 1. On `posts`, which will grow unboundedly, this becomes a real production problem.

| Property | Offset (`LIMIT … OFFSET`) | Cursor (`WHERE id < $cursor`) |
|---|---|---|
| Query cost | O(offset) — grows with depth | O(1) — index seek regardless of page |
| Stable results | ❌ Inserts shift rows between pages | ✅ Cursor anchors to a specific row |
| `COUNT(*)` needed | Yes (expensive on large tables) | No |
| Random access | ✅ Jump to page 47 | ❌ Must walk forward sequentially |
| Infinite scroll / feeds | Poor fit | Ideal fit |

### Why the compound `(created_at, id)` cursor matters

`created_at` alone is not unique — multiple posts can be published in the same second. Using `id` as a tiebreaker makes the cursor **stable and unique**, so the `WHERE` clause always places the page boundary at exactly one row.

### The `LIMIT N+1` trick

Fetching one extra row lets us know whether a next page exists in a single query, with no extra round-trip. We simply hide that row from the client and use its existence as the `hasMore` flag.

### When offset pagination is still fine

Offset pagination remains appropriate when you genuinely need **random access** (e.g., "jump to page 14 of search results in an admin panel") and the table is small enough that deep offsets are never reached. For a public feed like `/api/posts`, cursor pagination is the right model.

